write Rules:\nBased on the analysis, the following rules are selected to optimize the query:\n\n1. **FILTER_INTO_JOIN**: This rule will help push filter expressions into the join condition, potentially reducing the number of rows processed in the join.\n\n2. **FILTER_AGGREGATE_TRANSPOSE**: This rule will push filters past the aggregate, allowing the aggregation to work on a smaller set of data.\n\n3. **JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH**: This rule will push predicates in a join into the inputs to the join, which can help reduce the data size before the join operation.\n\n4. **FILTER_REDUCE_EXPRESSIONS**: This rule will reduce constants inside a filter, simplifying the filter conditions.\n\n### Transformation Steps:\n1. **Apply FILTER_INTO_JOIN**: Push the filters on `customer_address` and `customer_demographics` into the join conditions with `customer`.\n\n2. **Apply FILTER_AGGREGATE_TRANSPOSE**: Push the filters on `cd_marital_status`, `cd_education_status`, and `cd_gender` past the aggregation to reduce the data set before aggregation.\n\n3. **Apply JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH**: Push the join conditions involving `customer`, `store_sales`, `web_sales`, and `catalog_sales` into the respective subqueries to reduce the data size early.\n\n4. **Apply FILTER_REDUCE_EXPRESSIONS**: Simplify the filter conditions by reducing constants, especially in the subqueries.\n\nBy applying these rules, the query should become more efficient by reducing the number of rows processed in joins and aggregations, and by simplifying filter conditions.\n\n```python\n[\n    "FILTER_INTO_JOIN",\n    "FILTER_AGGREGATE_TRANSPOSE",\n    "JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH",\n    "FILTER_REDUCE_EXPRESSIONS"\n]\n```', 'time': 5.091615438461304}
